{{nihongo|'''''Dragon Slayer'''''|ドラゴンスレイヤー|Doragon Sureiyā}} is an [[action role-playing game]],<ref name="4Gamer" /><ref name="GameSetWatch" /> developed by [[Nihon Falcom]] and designed by Yoshio Kiya.<ref name="retro_3">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/JPNcomputers/Japanesecomputers3.htm|title=Retro Japanese Computers: Gaming's Final Frontier Retro Japanese Computers|page=3|author=John Szczepaniak|publisher=Hardcore Gaming 101|accessdate=2011-03-29}} Reprinted from {{citation|title=[[Retro Gamer]]|issue=67|year=2009}}</ref> It was originally released in 1984 for the [[PC-8801]], [[PC-9801]], [[X1 (computer)|X1]]<ref name=falcom/> and [[FM-7]],<ref name="fm7">{{cite web|title=Dragon Slayer|website=[[:ja:Oh!FM|Oh!FM7]]|url=http://fm-7.com/museum/softhouse/nihonfalcom/410900600.html|accessdate=2015-01-14}}</ref> and became a major success in Japan.<ref name="Xanadu" /> It was followed by an [[MSX]] port published by [[Square (video game company)|Square]] in 1985 (making it one of the first titles to be published by Square),<ref name="Dragon" /> a [[Cassette Vision|Super Cassette Vision]] by [[Epoch Co.|Epoch]] in 1986 and a [[Game Boy]] port by the same company in 1990 under the name {{nihongo|'''''Dragon Slayer I'''''|ドラゴンスレイヤーI|Doragon Sureiyā Wan}}. A version for [[PC-6000 series#PC-6001mkII|PC-6001mkII]] was in development but was never released.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Szczepaniak |first1=John |title=Poor Pay, Underage Staff And No Credits - Digging Into Falcom's Dark Past |url=https://www.timeextension.com/features/flashback-poor-pay-underage-staff-and-no-credits-digging-into-falcoms-dark-past |website=Time Extension |publisher=Hookshot Media Ltd. |access-date=18 December 2022 |date=21 October 2022}}</ref> A remake of ''Dragon Slayer'' is included in the ''Falcom Classics'' collection for the [[Sega Saturn]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Falcom Classics |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |issue=102|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=January 1998 |page=58}}</ref>

''Dragon Slayer'' began the [[Dragon Slayer (series)|''Dragon Slayer'' series]], a banner which encompasses a number of popular Falcom titles, such as ''[[Dragon Slayer II: Xanadu]]'', ''[[Sorcerian]]'', and ''[[Legacy of the Wizard]]''. It also includes ''[[Dragon Slayer: The Legend of Heroes]]'', which would later spawn over a dozen entries across multiple subseries.

== Gameplay ==
''Dragon Slayer'' is an early example of the [[action role-playing game]] genre, which it laid the foundations for.<ref name="4Gamer">Kamada Shigeaki, [http://www.4gamer.net/specials/retro/retro01.html レトロゲーム配信サイトと配信タイトルのピックアップ紹介記事「懐かし (Retro)] ([https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ja&u=http://www.4gamer.net/specials/retro/retro01.html Translation]), 4Gamer.net</ref> Building on the prototypical action role-playing elements of ''Panorama Toh'' (1983), created by Yoshio Kiya and Nihon Falcom,<ref>Sam Derboo (June 2, 2013), [http://blog.hardcoregaming101.net/2013/06/dark-age-of-jrpgs-6-panorama-toh-pc-88.html Dark Age of JRPGs (7): Panorama Toh ぱのらま島 - PC-88 (1983)], Hardcore Gaming 101</ref> as well as [[Namco]]'s ''[[The Tower of Druaga]]'' (1984),<ref name="1up_parish">{{cite web|title=What Happened to the Action RPG? |author=Jeremy Parish |website=[[1UP.com|1UP]] |year=2012 |url=http://www.1up.com/features/what-happened-action-rpg.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20150112012702/http://www.1up.com/features/what-happened-action-rpg.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-01-12 |accessdate=2015-01-14}}</ref> ''Dragon Slayer'' is often considered the first true action role-playing game.<ref name="4Gamer"/><ref name=GameSetWatch>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesetwatch.com/2006/07/column_compilation_catalog_fal_1.php|title=Falcom Classics|publisher=GameSetWatch|date=July 12, 2006|accessdate=2011-05-18}}</ref> In contrast to earlier turn-based [[roguelike]]s, ''Dragon Slayer'' was a [[dungeon crawl]] role-playing game that was entirely [[Real-time game|real-time]] with [[Action game|action-oriented]] combat,<ref name="GameSetWatch"/> combining [[Arcade game|arcade]] style [[Action game|action]] mechanics with traditional role-playing mechanics.<ref name="1up_parish"/>

''Dragon Slayer'' featured an [[Mini-map|in-game map]] to help with the dungeon-crawling, required [[Item (gaming)|item]] management due to the inventory being limited to one item at a time,<ref name="Dragon">Kurt Kalata, [http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/dragonslayer/dragonslayer.htm Dragon Slayer]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723142515/http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/dragonslayer/dragonslayer.htm |date=2011-07-23}}, Hardcore Gaming 101</ref> and featured item-based [[Puzzle game|puzzles]] similar to ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]''.<ref name="4Gamer" /> ''Dragon Slayer's'' [[Overhead perspective|overhead]] action-RPG formula was used in many later games.<ref name="Xanadu">Kurt Kalata, [http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/xanadu/xanadu.htm Xanadu], Hardcore Gaming 101</ref> Along with its competitor, ''[[Hydlide]]'', ''Dragon Slayer'' laid the foundations for the action RPG genre, including franchises such as ''[[Ys (series)|Ys]]'' and ''The Legend of Zelda''.<ref name="Dragon" /><ref name="Szczepaniak">John Szczepaniak (2016), ''The Untold History Of Japanese Game Developers, Volume 2'', pages 42-49</ref>

